1. Save output to a file (>)
ls > files.txt

This saves the output of ls into files.txt.

Example:

pwd > location.txt
2. Append output to a file (>>)
ls >> files.txt

Adds output to the end of the file without removing existing content.

3. Save Linux commands you typed
history > mycommands.txt

This creates a file containing all commands from your terminal history.

4. Create a file containing Linux commands manually
vi linux_commands.txt

Press i and type:

pwd - show current directory
ls - list files
cd - change directory
mkdir - create directory
rm - remove file
cp - copy files
mv - move/rename files

Save and exit:

Esc
:wq
5. Save command output and view it
uname -r > kernel_version.txt
cat kernel_version.txt
Check file contents
cat filename.txt

Example:

cat mycommands.txt
